word_summaries_chapter_86:
  86:1:1:"The first word of verse (86:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and noun. The prefixed preposition <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"by\" and is used to form an oath. The noun is feminine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">sīn mīm wāw</i> (<span class=\"at\">س م و</span>). Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  86:1:2:"The second word of verse (86:1) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and active participle. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The active participle is masculine and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṭā rā qāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">ط ر ق</span>)."
  86:2:1:"The first word of verse (86:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A conjunction and interrogative noun. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">wa</i> is usually translated as \"and\"."
  86:2:2:"The second word of verse (86:2) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A verb and object pronoun. The form IV perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>) is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">dāl rā yā</i> (<span class=\"at\">د ر ي</span>). The attached object pronoun is second person masculine singular."
  86:2:3:"The third word of verse (86:2) is an interrogative noun."
  86:2:4:"The fourth word of verse (86:2) is a masculine active participle and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ṭā rā qāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">ط ر ق</span>)."
  86:3:1:"The first word of verse (86:3) is a masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn jīm mīm</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ج م</span>)."
  86:3:2:"The second word of verse (86:3) is a masculine active participle and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">thā qāf bā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ث ق ب</span>)."
  86:4:1:"The first word of verse (86:4) is a negative particle."
  86:4:2:"The second word of verse (86:4) is a masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">kāf lām lām</i> (<span class=\"at\">ك ل ل</span>)."
  86:4:3:"The third word of verse (86:4) is an indefinite feminine singular noun and is in the genitive case (<span class=\"at\">مجرور</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn fā sīn</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ف س</span>)."
  86:4:4:"The fourth word of verse (86:4) is an exceptive particle."
  86:4:5:"The fifth word of verse (86:4) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and object pronoun. The attached object pronoun is third person feminine singular. Together the segments form a preposition phrase known as <i class=\"ab\">jār wa majrūr</i> (<span class=\"at\">جار ومجرور</span>)."
  86:4:6:"The sixth word of verse (86:4) is an indefinite masculine active participle and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The active participle's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">ḥā fā ẓā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ح ف ظ</span>)."
  86:5:1:"The first word of verse (86:5) is divided into 3 morphological segments. A conjunction, imperative particle and verb. The prefixed conjunction <i class=\"ab\">fa</i> is usually translated as \"and\". The prefixed particle <i class=\"ab\">lām</i> is usually translated as \"let\" and is used to form an imperative construction. The imperfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل مضارع</span>) is third person masculine singular and is in the jussive mood (<span class=\"at\">مجزوم</span>). The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">nūn ẓā rā</i> (<span class=\"at\">ن ظ ر</span>)."
  86:5:2:"The second word of verse (86:5) is a masculine noun and is in the nominative case (<span class=\"at\">مرفوع</span>). The noun's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">hamza nūn sīn</i> (<span class=\"at\">أ ن س</span>)."
  86:5:3:"The third word of verse (86:5) is divided into 2 morphological segments. A preposition and relative pronoun."
  86:5:4:"The fourth word of verse (86:5) is a passive perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā lām qāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ ل ق</span>)."
  86:6:1:"The first word of verse (86:6) is a passive perfect verb (<span class=\"at\">فعل ماض</span>). The verb is third person masculine singular. The verb's triliteral root is <i class=\"ab\">khā lām qāf</i> (<span class=\"at\">خ ل ق</span>)."
